            <person xml:id="pers1261">
               <p><persName>Law</persName>&apos;s brief academic and ecclesiastical career came to
                  an end in <date when="1716">1716</date> when he refused to abjure allegiance to
                  the lineage of <persName>James</persName>, upon <persName>George I</persName>
                  taking the throne of <placeName>England</placeName>. He focused his energy from
                  that point on devotional writings, among which <hi rend="italic">Serious Call to a
                     Devout and Holy Life</hi> (<date when="1728">1728</date>) and <hi rend="italic"
                     >Practical Treatise upon Christian Perfection</hi> (<date when="1726"
                     >1726</date>) greatly influenced <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> during his formative years. <persName><ptr
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> corresponded with
                     <persName>Law</persName> appreciatively in the early <date>1730s</date>. After
                  <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s evangelical conversion in <date when="1738"
                     >1738</date>, their correspondence became more critical in tone. See <hi
                     rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>,
                  198.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
